


Chief Exec Steps Down At Johnson Products - tribunedigital-chicagotribune




 



Chief Exec Steps Down At Johnson ProductsMarch 10, 1992Johnson Products Co. chief Eric G. Johnson has abruptly left that company, apparently the latest victim of squabbling within its controlling family.The Chicago ethnic hair-care products company, known for such brands as Gentle Treatment and Ultra Sheen, disclosed Eric Johnson`s departure Monday, following weekend reports of his ouster in Crain`s Chicago Business.FOR THE RECORD - Additional material published March 11, 1992:Corrections and clarifications.In a March 10 story in the Business section on a management shakeup at Johnson Products Inc., it was stated incorrectly that Eric G. Johnson asked his two brothers, John and George Jr., to leave the company soon after he became chief executive in 1989. George Johnson Sr., whoresigned from the company in 1989, said George Jr. left the company to pursue a career in the music industry. George Sr. said he, not Eric, dismissed John from the firm, but declined to elaborate. George Jr. confirmed he chose to leave the company. Efforts to reach John forcomment were unsuccessful. The Tribune regrets the errors.Eric Johnson had been widely credited for a comeback in the company`s fortunes in recent years. With its earnings prospects good, the company in January paid its first dividend since 1980.On the American Stock Exchange, Johnson Products` shares closed Monday at $19.50, off 87 cents.In a statement, the company said Eric Johnson resigned as president, chief executive and a director ``to pursue personal business interests.``Efforts to reach him and other company officials for comment were unsuccessful.The company didn`t name a successor, but said it will form an ``office of the president`` to be filled by several key executives, none of whom was identified.Joan B. Johnson, 62, the company`s controlling stockholder and chairman as well as Eric`s mother, acknowledged the ``significant contribution`` made by her 40-year-old son.``I understand his decision and wish him well in the future,`` she said in the statement.Their relationship has displayed signs of strain in the last year.Last May, Eric Johnson submitted a proposal to the company`s board that contemplated his mother acquiring the nearly 40 percent of shares in public hands for $17.25 a share, or about $8 million. But his mother wouldn`t commit to the plan and he withdrew it two months later.His departure comes 4 1/2 months after he signed a new employment agreement that was to run until Oct. 28, 1994. Under that agreement, he could receive severance payments of up to two years of his base salary ($300,000)plus bonus.In 1972, Eric Johnson joined the company founded by his father, George, and his mother. Eric became president in 1988 and chief executive a year later, when his parents divorced and George Johnson resigned, turning over his shares to his ex-wife.Joan Johnson today controls through trusts 58.2 percent of the company stock. Other officers and directors control a combined 1.4 percent.Soon after becoming chief executive, Eric Johnson created turmoil within the family by asking his two brothers to leave the company, apparently because he was dissatisfied with their productivity.A shareholder suit, filed last year to block the proposed buyout, referred to the move against the brothers.It quoted Eric Johnson as saying, ``We`re not a social organization that has memberships. My main goal is to be operating a profitable business.``Crain`s quoted sources as saying Eric Johnson`s departure could allow his 27-year-old sister, Joan M. Johnson, to jump several rungs on the corporate ladder.The newspaper said she joined the company a year ago as director of market research.


