Johnson Boss Drops Bid To Go Private - tribunedigital-chicagotribune




 



Johnson Boss Drops Bid To Go PrivateJune 26, 1991|By Charles Storch.The president of Johnson Products Co. on Tuesday abandoned his proposal to take the firm private amid indications he lacked support from its controlling stockholder, his mother.Eric G. Johnson, 40, president and chief executive of the Chicago-based hair products firm, said in a statement he was withdrawing the $8 million proposal because he was unable to negotiate a transaction that would meet``the needs of all parties involved.``The company didn`t elaborate on his statement, but it is presumed one of those parties was Eric`s mother, Joan B. Johnson. She is the company`s chairwoman and controls 59.4 percent of its shares.Mrs. Johnson, 62, previously disclosed she supported ``in principle`` the idea of the company going private and had discussed the idea with her son. She said she favored any transaction that was fair to public shareholders and met her ``financial security requirements.``However, she also made it clear she wasn`t a member of her son`s buyout group and hadn`t decided whether to back the bid.In a statement Tuesday, Mrs. Johnson said only that she intends to remain the company`s majority stockholder. An attorney representing her declined to elaborate on her statement or her position on the buyout proposal.On May 28, Johnson Products disclosed that a group led by Eric Johnson proposed acquiring the 39 percent of Johnson Products stock in public hands for $17.25 a share, or about $8 million.The proposal called for Mrs. Johnson to own initially all of the company`s stock, but to reduce gradually her ownership interest ``to give senior management a substantial stake.``Eric Johnson said Tuesday: ``The proposed transaction required meeting the needs of all parties involved. However, the overriding objective has always been, and remains, enhancing the long-term viability of the company. We were unable to negotiate a transaction which would meet all of these goals.`` His statement came after the stock market`s close. On the American Stock Exchange, Johnson Products stock closed unchanged Tuesday at $14.50 a share.Johnson Products, one of the city`s most prominent minority-controlled companies, manufactures such hair-care products as Gentle-Treatment, Ultra Sheen, and Classy Curl.After several rocky years, the company`s financial performance has improved since Eric Johnson became chief executive in October 1989.In the fiscal year that ended last August, the company earned $2.1 million on sales of $33.5 million. For the first six months of fiscal 1991, it earned $1.2 million on sales of $16.3 million.A shareholder suit challenged the buyout bid. The suit was filed last month in Delaware, where the company is incorporated.


